\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is absolutely continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}_{y}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{y}\in K\left[h\right](y,t)$
\end_inset

 for almost all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\mathcal{I}_{y}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $K\left[\cdot\right]$
\end_inset

 denotes the Filippov set-valued map defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Equation 2b"
key "Paden1987"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A solution is called 
\shape italic
complete
\shape default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}_{y}$
\end_inset

 is unbounded.
 A solution 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}:[t_{0},t_{2})\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{y}=h(y,t)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\shape italic
proper right extension
\shape default
 of a solution 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}:[t_{0},t_{1})\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{y}=h(y,t)$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}>t_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}(t)=y_{1}(t)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall t\in[t_{0},t_{1})$
\end_inset

.
 A solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{y}=h(y,t)$
\end_inset

 is called 
\shape italic
maximal
