\begin_layout Example
\noindent
Consider a dynamic neural network given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{\nu}=\mathrm{proj}\{W^{T}\sigma(V^{T}x),\nu\},\label{eq:neural_network}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{proj}\{\cdot,\cdot\}$
\end_inset

 denotes the smooth projection operator in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cai2006a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 that guarantees 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \nu\right\Vert \leq\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma:\mathbb{R}^{L}\to\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

 denotes a globally bounded continuous activation function, and 
\begin_inset Formula $W\in\mathbb{R}^{m\times L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V\in\mathbb{R}^{L\times n}$
\end_inset

 are constant
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Patre2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for continuous adaptive weight updates.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 matrices of outer and inner-layer weights, respectively.
 Using 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Property 3"
key "Cai2006a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 is globally bounded, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\nu}$
\end_inset

 can be bounded by a constant, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \dot{\nu}\right\Vert \leq\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Taking the time-derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\nu}$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{\nu}=\frac{d}{dt}(\mathrm{proj}\{W^{T}\sigma(V^{T}x),\nu\})=\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial y}(\mathrm{proj}\{y,\nu\})\right|_{y=W^{T}\sigma(V^{T}x)}\frac{d}{dt}(W^{T}\sigma(V^{T}x))+\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial y}(\mathrm{proj}\{W^{T}\sigma(V^{T}x),y\})\right|_{y=\nu}\dot{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 Based on the structure of the projection operator in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Eq. 7"
key "Cai2006a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the terms 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial y}(\mathrm{proj}\{y,\nu\})\right|_{y=W^{T}\sigma(V^{T}x)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial y}(\mathrm{proj}\{W^{T}\sigma(V^{T}x),y\})\right|_{y=\nu}$
\end_inset

 can be bounded by some known functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Additionally, based on the right-hand-side of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:edot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dt}(W^{T}\sigma(V^{T}x))=W^{T}\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\sigma(y)\right|_{y=V^{T}x}V^{T}\dot{x}=W^{T}\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\sigma(y)\right|_{y=V^{T}x}V^{T}(\dot{x}_{d}+r-\alpha e)$
\end_inset

 can be bounded by some known continuous function of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{\nu}$
\end_inset

 can be bounded as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \ddot{\nu}\right\Vert \leq\eta_{3}+\eta_{4}\left\Vert z\right\Vert +\rho_{21}\left(\left\Vert z\right\Vert \right)\left\Vert z\right\Vert $
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the dynamic neural network in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:neural_network"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) satisfies Assumption 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "assm:bounded_uncertainty"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
