.
 Consider the dynamical neural network given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu(t)=\int_{0}^{t}\mathrm{proj}\{\hat{W}^{T}(\tau)\sigma(\hat{V}^{T}(\tau)x(\tau)),\nu(\tau),\eta_{2}\}d\tau$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{W}:\mathcal{I}\to\mathbb{R}^{m\times L}$
\end_inset

 is the matrix of outer-layer weights, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}:\mathcal{I}\to\mathbb{R}^{L\times n}$
\end_inset

 is the matrix of inner-layer weights, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma:\mathbb{R}^{L}\to\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

 denotes a globally bounded continuous activation function with a globally
 bounded gradient.
 Then, differentiating 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 using Leibniz rule yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\nu}=\mathrm{proj}\{\hat{W}^{T}\sigma(\hat{V}^{T}x),\nu,\eta_{2}\}$
\end_inset

.
 The inner and outer-layer weights are designed using the projection-based
 update laws 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Patre2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\hat{W}}=\mathrm{proj}\{\Gamma_{1}\hat{\sigma}^{\prime}\hat{V}^{T}\dot{x}_{d}e^{T},\hat{W},\bar{W}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\hat{V}}=\mathrm{proj}\{\Gamma_{2}\dot{x}_{d}(\hat{\sigma}^{\prime T}\hat{W}e)^{T},\hat{V},\bar{V}\}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{1}\in\mathbb{R}^{L\times L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma_{2}\in\mathbb{R}^{m\times m}$
\end_inset

 are positive-definite adaptation gains, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 is a short-hand notation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\frac{\partial\sigma(y)}{\partial y}\right|_{y=\hat{V}^{T}x}$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{\nu}=\frac{d}{dt}(\mathrm{proj}\{\hat{W}^{T}\sigma(\hat{V}^{T}x),\nu,\eta_{2}\})=\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial y}(\mathrm{proj}\{y,\nu,\eta_{2}\})\right|_{y=\hat{W}^{T}\sigma(\hat{V}^{T}x)}\frac{d}{dt}(\hat{W}^{T}\sigma(\hat{V}^{T}x))+\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial y}(\mathrm{proj}\{\hat{W}^{T}\sigma(\hat{V}^{T}x),y,\eta_{2}\})\right|_{y=\nu}\dot{\nu}.$
\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \frac{\partial}{\partial y}(\mathrm{proj}\{y,\nu,\eta_{2}\})\right\Vert \leq1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall y\in\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The structure of the closed-loop error system in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rdot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) may appear similar to a higher order sliding-mode design (cf., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Levant1993"
literal "false"

\end_inset

); however, there are some remarkable differences to highlight.
 Specifically, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\mathrm{sgn}\left(e\right)$
\end_inset

 term in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rdot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) would need to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\mathrm{sgn}\left(r\right)$
\end_inset

 to facilitate the analysis for a standard continuous higher-order sliding-mode
 design.
 Since sensor measurements for the highest order derivative (e.g., 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{e}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

) may not be available for feedback, the controller in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:controlinput"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is designed to depend only on state measurements.
 Additionally, the closed-loop error system in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:edot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rdot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is also different from a super-twisting system, since (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:edot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) would require an additional 
\begin_inset Formula $-\left|e\right|^{1/2}\mathrm{sgn}(e)$
\end_inset

 term to facilitate a super-twisting design, which needs a different analysis
 approach 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gonzalez.Moreno.ea2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

