\begin_layout Standard
Following the development in Section II, every Filippov solution to (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dynamicsystem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mudot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) with the controller in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:controlinput"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) corresponds to a Filippov solution of the transformed system in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:edot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rdot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Additionally, a P-function is introduced to facilitate the construction
 of a candidate Lyapunov function for analyzing the stability and convergence
 properties of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 The P-function is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $P:\mathcal{I}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and is defined as a Filippov solution to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{P}=-\lambda_{P}P-L,\label{eq:Pdot}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{P}\in\mathbb{R}_{>0}$
\end_inset

 is an auxiliary constant, and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
L & \triangleq & r^{T}N_{B}-r^{T}\beta\mathrm{sgn}\left(e\right)\nonumber \\
 &  & -\left(\gamma_{4}+\rho_{2}\left(\left\Vert z\right\Vert \right)\right)\left\Vert z\right\Vert \left\Vert e\right\Vert _{1},\label{eq:L}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \cdot\right\Vert _{1}$
\end_inset

 denotes the 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-norm, and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(t_{0})=\beta\left\Vert e(t_{0})\right\Vert _{1}-e^{T}(t_{0})N_{B}(t_{0}).\label{eq:P0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The analytical solution to (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Pdot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is derived in Lemma 3.
 To facilitate the inclusion of the P-function in the candidate Lyapunov
 function, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is designed to be non-negative under certain gain conditions as described
 in Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:P>0"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:Psol"

\end_inset

Given some Filippov solutions, 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, to (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:edot"
