The set 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 can also be represented as 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\{t\in\mathcal{I}|\exists i\in\{1,2,\ldots,n\}\,\textrm{s.t.}\,e_{i}\left(t\right)=0\:\wedge r_{i}(t)-\alpha e_{i}(t)\neq0\}=\{t\in\mathcal{I}|\exists i\in\{1,2,\ldots,n\}\,\textrm{s.t.}\,e_{i}\left(t\right)=0\:\wedge\dot{e}_{i}(t)\neq0\}$
\end_inset

 to facilitate the subsequent analysis using the dynamics in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rdot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Select 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in T$
\end_inset

, which yields 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}(a)=0$
\end_inset

 using the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{e}_{i}(a)\neq0$
\end_inset

, we can assume without loss of generality that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{e}_{i}(a)>0$
\end_inset

; the proof easily extends for 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{e}_{i}(a)<0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 are absolutely continuous, it follows from (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:edot"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{e}$
\end_inset

 is continuous.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{e}_{i}(a)>0$
\end_inset

 and continuity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{e}$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{e}_{i}(t)>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\left(a-\delta,a+\delta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Based on 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{e}_{i}(t)>0$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{t}\dot{e}_{i}(\tau)d\tau>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\left(a,a+\delta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then, using 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}(a)=0$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{t}\dot{e}_{i}(\tau)d\tau=e_{i}(t)-e_{i}(a)=e_{i}(t)>0$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $-\int_{t}^{a}\dot{e}_{i}(\tau)d\tau=e_{i}(t)-e_{i}(a)=e_{i}(t)<0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\left(a-\delta,a\right)$
\end_inset

, implying 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}(t)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\left(a-\delta,a+\delta\right)\backslash\left\{ a\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 If more than one component has 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}(a)=0$
\end_inset

, we select the intersection of each neighborhood found above, represented
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $U(a)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, there exists a neighborhood, 
\begin_inset Formula $U(a)$
\end_inset

, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in T$
\end_inset

, s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}(t)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all time-instants 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in U(a)\backslash\left\{ a\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{1,2,\ldots,n\}$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in T$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}(t)=0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{1,2,\ldots,n\}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $U(a)\cap T=\{a\}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in T$
\end_inset

; therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is discrete and consequently has measure zero.
\end_layout

